Member Typedef Documentation

typedef uint32_t Bitvector::data_word_type

Data word type.

Bitvectors are stored as arrays of data words, each containing data_word_bits bits. For special purposes it may be faster or easier to manipulate data words directly.

Bitvector::Bit Bitvector::force_bit ( int  i  )  [inline]

Return the bit at position i, extending if necessary.

If i >= size(), then the Bitvector is resize()d to length i+1, which adds false bits to fill out the vector.

Precondition:
0 <= i
Postcondition:
i < size()

void Bitvector::offset_or ( const Bitvector &  x,
int  offset 
)

Modify this Bitvector by bitwise or with an offset x.

Parameters:
x bitwise or operand
offset initial offset
Precondition:
offset >= 0 && offset + x.size() <= size()

Logically shifts x to start at position offset, then performs a bitwise or. a.offset_or(b, offset) is equivalent to: 

 for (int i = 0; i < b.size(); ++i)
     a[offset+i] |= b[i];

void Bitvector::or_with_difference ( const Bitvector &  x,
Bitvector &  difference 
)

Modify this Bitvector by bitwise or, returning difference.

Parameters:
x bitwise or operand
[out] difference set to (x - old *this)
Precondition:
x.size() == size()
Postcondition:
difference.size() == size()
x | *this == *this
(difference & *this & x) == difference

Same as operator|=, but additionally preserves any change in this Bitvector. Any newly set bits are returned in difference.
